        # Characteristics of the Terminal Deoxynucleotidyl Transferase
        The terminal deoxynucleotidyltransferase (TdT) is an enzyme that possesses the unusual ability to incorporate nucleotides in a template-independent manner using only single-stranded DNA as the nucleic acid substrate [3](#citation3). 
         
        Like all DNA polymerases, the TdT also requires divalent metal ions for catalysis of the phosphoryl transfer reaction associated with nucleotide incorporation. 
        However, the TdT is uniquely capable of using a variety of divalent cations such as $Co^{2+}$, $Mn^{2+}$, $Zn^{2+}$, and $Mg^{2+}$ [4](#citation4). 
         
        Another advantage of using the TdT is that the enzyme utilizes a wide variety of nucleotide analogues such as 2′,3′-dideoxynucleotides, p-nitrophenylethyl triphosphate, p-nitrophenyl triphosphate, 2′-deoxy-L-ribonucleoside 5′-triphosphates, and dinucleoside 5′,5′-tetraphosphates [4](#citation4). 
        This can be used for increasing the data capacity for DNA data storage. The idea is further elaborated in our [Outlook](https://2021.igem.org/Team:Aachen/Outlook#Increaseofthedatacapacity). 
         
        Since we wanted to incorporate nucleotides in a controlled manner, we had to interrupt the reaction in the standard TdT reactions. 
        Heat and many different metal chelators can be used for inhibiting the TdT activity, such as o-phenanthroline, EDTA, triethylene-tetramine, α:α'-bipyridyl, and cysteine [5](#citation5). 
        
